	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You might as well write your own game from scratch, because there's no way in hell you're "backwards porting" an SNES game to the NES without the source code (and even then, it'd take a herculean amount of effort). Here's just a few of the problems you'd encounter:
<br />
<br />- converting 16-bit code to 8-bit
<br />- rewriting the sound engine
<br />- rewriting the graphics routines
<br />- rewriting the control routines (the SNES has 4 more buttons than the NES)
<br />- bankswitching (the NES can only access 32KB of ROM at a time)
<br />
<br />Also, the idea of "combining ROMs" is laughable, even if their engines seem similar. Do you honestly have any idea what you're talking about?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


